GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
S 1
SENATE BILL 874
Short Title: Licensing Certain Fire Safety Equipment. (Public)
Sponsors: Senator Burgin (Primary Sponsor).
Referred to: Rules and Operations of the Senate
April 29, 2026
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO REQUIRE LICENSING AND PERMITTING FOR INDIVIDUALS AND FIRMS
3 THAT INSTALL AND SERVICE PORTABLE FIRE EXTINGUISHERS AND FIRE
4 SUPPRESSION SYSTEMS.
5 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
6 SECTION 1. Chapter 58 of the General Statutes is amended by adding a new Article
7 to read:
8 "Article 82C.
9 "Licensing and Permitting for the Installation and Servicing of Portable Fire Extinguishers and
10 Fire Suppression Systems.
11 "§ 58-82C-1. Definitions.
12 The following definitions apply in this Article:
13 (1) Engineered special hazard fire suppression system. – A fire suppression
14 system having pipe lengths, number of fittings, number and types of nozzles,
15 suppression agent flow rates, and nozzle pressures calculated based on
16 appropriate standards of the National Fire Protection Association. An
17 engineered fire suppression system may include other components, including,
18 but not limited to, detection devices, alarm devices, and control devices as
19 tested and approved by a nationally recognized testing laboratory, where the
20 component's manufacturer determines the component is compatible with the
21 fire suppression system.
22 (2) Fire suppression system. – Any firefighting system employing a suppression
23 agent with the purpose of controlling, suppressing, or extinguishing a fire in a
24 specific hazard, including pre-engineered kitchen fire suppression systems,
25 pre-engineered industrial fire suppression systems, and engineered special
26 hazard fire suppression systems.
27 (3) Firm. – Any business, person, partnership, organization, association,
28 corporation, contractor, subcontractor, or individual.
29 (4) Industrial fire suppression system. – A pre-engineered automatic fire
30 extinguishing system provided for the protection of property or equipment as
31 described by the manufacturer other than those systems covered under the
32 definition of kitchen fire suppression system.
33 (5) Kitchen fire suppression system. – An automatic fire extinguishing system
34 provided for the protection of grease removal devices, hoods, duct systems,
35 and cooking equipment. This term also includes "restaurant fire suppression
36 system."
*S874-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (6) License. – The document issued by the State Fire Marshal which authorizes a
2 firm to engage in the business of installation, repair, recharging, inspection,
3 service, or testing of fire suppression systems or portable fire extinguishers.
4 (7) Permit. – The document issued by the State Fire Marshal which authorizes an
5 individual to install, inspect, repair, recharge, service, or test fire suppression
6 systems or portable fire extinguishers.
7 (8) Portable fire extinguisher. – A portable device containing an extinguishing
8 agent that can be expelled under pressure for the purpose of suppressing or
9 extinguishing a fire.
10 (9) Pre-engineered fire suppression system. – Any system having predetermined
11 flow rates, nozzle pressures, and quantities of an extinguishing agent.
12 (10) State Fire Marshal. – The head of the North Carolina Office of the State Fire
13 Marshal as defined in G.S. 58-78A-1(c).
14 (11) Suppression agent. – A currently recognized agent or water additive required
15 to control, suppress, or extinguish a fire.
16 "§ 58-82C-2. State Fire Marshal to administer Article; rules and regulations.
17 (a) The State Fire Marshal, through the Office of the State Fire Marshal, shall have full
18 power and authority to administer the provisions of this Article, including adopting rules to
19 enforce the purposes and provisions of this Article.
20 (b) The State Fire Marshal shall establish rules for the following:
21 (1) Proper installation, inspection, recharging, repairing, servicing, or testing of
22 fire suppression systems or portable fire extinguishers.
23 (2) Required specifications as to the number, type, size, shape, color, and
24 information and data contained on service tags to be attached to all portable
25 fire extinguishers and fire suppression systems covered by this Article when
26 they are installed, inspected, recharged, repaired, serviced, or tested.
27 (c) The State Fire Marshal may adopt by rule the applicable standards of the National
28 Fire Protection Association or another nationally recognized organization if the standards are
29 judged by the State Fire Marshal to be suitable for the enforcement of this Article. All fire
30 suppression systems and portable fire extinguishers covered by G.S. 58-82C-3 shall be installed,
31 inspected, recharged, repaired, serviced, or tested in compliance with this Article and with the
32 State Fire Marshal's rules.
33 (d) The State Fire Marshal may adopt rules to require an applicant for a license or permit
34 to take an examination as to the applicant's competence to be licensed or permitted under this
35 Article. If required, the applicant must take and pass the examination according to requirements
36 prescribed by the State Fire Marshal.
37 (e) The State Fire Marshal is authorized to apply for and receive grants for the
38 administration of this Article from parties interested in upgrading and improving the quality of
39 fire protection provided by portable fire extinguishers or fire suppression systems.
40 "§ 58-82C-3. Compliance with this Article; license and permit requirement.
41 (a) Except as otherwise provided by this Article, no firm may install, inspect, repair,
42 recharge, service, or test any of the following fire suppression systems or portable fire
43 extinguishers that are required by the State Fire Marshal's rules or by other State or local fire
44 safety rules, unless the firm is licensed under the provisions of this Article:
45 (1) Portable fire extinguishers.
46 (2) Pre-engineered kitchen fire suppression systems.
47 (3) Pre-engineered industrial fire suppression systems.
48 (4) Engineered special hazard fire suppression systems.
49 (b) Except as otherwise provided by this Article, no individual may install, inspect,
50 repair, recharge, service, or test any of the following fire suppression systems or portable fire
Page 2 Senate Bill 874-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 extinguishers that are required by the State Fire Marshal's rules or by other State or local fire
2 safety rules, unless the individual is permitted under the provisions of this Article:
3 (1) Portable fire extinguishers.
4 (2) Pre-engineered kitchen fire suppression systems.
5 (3) Pre-engineered industrial fire suppression systems.
6 (4) Engineered special hazard fire suppression systems.
7 (c) It shall be unlawful for an individual to install, inspect, recharge, repair, service, or
8 test any portable fire extinguisher or fire suppression system without attaching the required tag
9 or tags completed in detail, including the actual month, day, and year the work was performed,
10 or to use a tag not meeting the specifications set forth by the State Fire Marshal.
11 (d) The permit established by subsection (b) of this section shall not be required for any
12 individual employed by any firm or governmental entity that engages only in installing,
13 inspecting, recharging, repairing, servicing, or testing of portable fire extinguishers or fire
14 suppression systems owned by the firm and installed on property under the control of the firm.
15 These individuals shall remain subject to the rules and regulations adopted pursuant to this
16 Article.
17 (e) The provisions of this Article do not apply to any of the following:
18 (1) Fire chiefs, fire marshals, fire inspectors, or insurance company inspectors
19 with regard to the routine visual inspection of pre-engineered fire suppression
20 systems or portable fire extinguishers.
21 (2) Any firm that engages only in the routine visual inspection of fire suppression
22 systems or portable fire extinguishers owned by the firm and installed on
23 property under the control of the firm.
24 "§ 58-82C-4. License and permit fees.
25 (a) A nonrefundable license fee of two hundred fifty dollars ($250.00) shall be paid to
26 the State Fire Marshal with each application for the issuance of a license under this Article.
27 (b) Except as otherwise provided by G.S. 93B-15.1(k), a nonrefundable permit fee of one
28 hundred dollars ($100.00) shall be paid to the State Fire Marshal with each application for the
29 issuance of a permit under this Article.
30 (c) The fees required by this Article shall not apply to employees of federal, State, or
31 local governments or to a member of a legally organized fire department while acting in the
32 member's official capacity.
33 "§ 58-82C-5. Requirements for issuance of license.
34 (a) Before approving a license for a firm pursuant to G.S. 58-82C-3, the State Fire
35 Marshal shall find that the firm has:
36 (1) Submitted a completed application pursuant to G.S. 58-82C-8.
37 (2) Submitted to the State Fire Marshal evidence satisfactory to the State Fire
38 Marshal that the applicant is a lawfully existing individual or entity and, if the
39 applicant is required by law to register with the Secretary of State or obtain
40 authority to transact business or conduct affairs in this State, that the applicant
41 has done so.
42 (3) Not committed any act that is a ground for denial, suspension, probation,
43 revocation, or nonrenewal set forth in G.S. 58-82C-11.
44 (4) Satisfied all requirements of this Article.
45 (5) Been determined, by inspection of the State Fire Marshal, to possess the
46 equipment required for the activities the applicant requests to be licensed to
47 perform. If the applicant includes in the request the high-pressure hydrostatic
48 testing of equipment, the applicant must submit a copy of its United States
49 Department of Transportation approval and renewals.
50 (6) Submitted to the State Fire Marshal proof of a valid comprehensive liability
51 insurance policy purchased from an insurer authorized to do business in North
Senate Bill 874-First Edition Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 Carolina. The coverage must include bodily injury and property damage,
2 products liability, completed operations, and contractual liability. The proof
3 of insurance must also be provided before any license can be renewed. The
4 minimum amount of the coverage shall be one million dollars ($1,000,000) or
5 any other amount as specified by the State Fire Marshal. An insurer which
6 provides this coverage shall notify the State Fire Marshal of any change in
7 coverage.
8 (7) Paid the applicable fees set forth in G.S. 58-82C-4.
9 (8) Paid a nonrefundable filing fee fixed by rule of the State Fire Marshal when
10 filing an application for an examination if the State Fire Marshal requires an
11 examination pursuant to this Article.
12 (9) Successfully passed any examination if the State Fire Marshal requires an
13 examination pursuant to this Article.
14 (b) Before approving a permit for an individual pursuant to G.S. 58-82C-3, the State Fire
15 Marshal shall find that the individual has:
16 (1) Submitted a completed application pursuant to G.S. 58-82C-8.
17 (2) Not committed any act that is a ground for denial, suspension, probation,
18 revocation, or nonrenewal set forth in G.S. 58-82C-11.
19 (3) Satisfied all requirements of this Article.
20 (4) Paid the applicable fees set forth in G.S. 58-82C-4, except as otherwise
21 provided by G.S. 93B-15.1(k).
22 (5) Paid a nonrefundable filing fee fixed by rule of the State Fire Marshal when
23 filing an application for an examination if the State Fire Marshal requires an
24 examination pursuant to this Article.
25 (6) Successfully passed any examination if the State Fire Marshal requires an
26 examination pursuant to this Article.
27 "§ 58-82C-6. Production of license or permit on demand.
28 (a) Every permittee must have a valid permit upon his or her person at all times while
29 engaging in the installation, inspection, recharging, repairing, servicing, or testing of fire
30 suppression systems or portable fire extinguishers.
31 (b) Every licensee or permittee must be able to produce a valid license or valid permit, as
32 appropriate, upon demand by the State Fire Marshal or his or her representatives or by any local
33 authority having jurisdiction for fire protection or prevention or by any individual for whom the
34 licensee or permittee solicits to perform any of the activities covered by this Article.
35 "§ 58-82C-7. Reciprocity.
36 (a) The State Fire Marshal shall issue an individual permit under this Article to an
37 applicant who qualifies under G.S. 93B-15.1 or G.S. 93B-15.3, subject to those sections.
38 (b) In addition to subsection (a) of this section, the State Fire Marshal may issue a license
39 to a firm that holds a comparable valid out-of-state credential, or may issue a permit to an
40 individual who holds a comparable valid out-of-state credential, if the State Fire Marshal
41 determines that the other jurisdiction's requirements are substantially equivalent to the
42 requirements of this Article and the applicant has paid any applicable fees required by this
43 Article.
44 (c) Nothing in this section limits the applicability of G.S. 93B-15.1 or G.S. 93B-15.3.
45 "§ 58-82C-8. Forms of licenses, permits, and applications; information required.
46 (a) A firm applying for a license or an individual applying for a permit under this Article
47 shall apply on a form prescribed by the State Fire Marshal. The application shall declare, under
48 penalty of denial, suspension, or revocation of the license or permit, that the statements made in
49 the application are true, correct, and complete to the best of the applicant's knowledge and belief.
50 An application by a firm shall be executed by an owner, officer, or other authorized representative
51 of the firm.
Page 4 Senate Bill 874-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (b) Permit applications shall include the name of the licensee employing the applicant or
2 the name of the firm or governmental entity pursuant to the exemptions found in G.S. 58-82C-3,
3 except that an applicant proceeding under G.S. 93B-15.1 or G.S. 93B-15.3 is not required to
4 provide that information at the time of application.
5 (c) Each license or permit issued by the State Fire Marshal under this Article shall clearly
6 state the activity or activities for which the licensee or permittee has been issued the license or
7 permit to perform. The licensee or permittee shall not perform any activity not noted on a license
8 or permit issued by the State Fire Marshal.
9 (d) A licensee or permittee shall notify the State Fire Marshal within 30 days of any
10 change to the information provided to the State Fire Marshal on the license or permit application.
11 (e) The State Fire Marshal shall give an applicant 60 days to correct any deficiencies
12 discovered by inspection.
13 "§ 58-82C-9. Terms of licenses and permits; failure to renew.
14 (a) The licenses and permits required by this Article shall be issued by the State Fire
15 Marshal for each license year beginning January 1 and expiring the following December 31.
16 (b) The failure to renew a license or permit by December 31 will cause the license or
17 permit to become inoperative. A license or permit which is inoperative because of the failure to
18 renew the license or permit shall be restored upon payment of the applicable fee, plus a penalty
19 equal to the applicable fee, if the fees are paid within 90 days of expiration. After 90 days, the
20 former licensees and former permittees must apply for new licenses and permits as required for
21 an initial license or permit.
22 "§ 58-82C-10. License or permit sanction and denial procedures.
23 (a) The suspension, placing on probation, revocation, denial, or refusal to renew any
24 license or permit under this Article shall be in accordance with the provisions of Chapter 150B
25 of the General Statutes.
26 (b) Whenever the State Fire Marshal denies an initial application or an application for a
27 reissuance of a license or permit under this Article, the State Fire Marshal shall notify the
28 applicant and advise, in writing, the applicant of the reasons for the denial of the license or permit.
29 The applicant may also be denied for any reasons for which a license or permit may be suspended,
30 revoked, or not renewed under G.S. 58-82C-11.
31 (c) In order for an applicant to be entitled to a review of the State Fire Marshal's action
32 to determine the reasonableness of the action, the applicant must make a written demand upon
33 the State Fire Marshal for a review no later than 30 days after service of the notification upon the
34 applicant. The review shall be completed without undue delay, and the applicant shall be notified
35 promptly in writing of the outcome of the review.
36 (d) In order for an applicant who disagrees with the outcome of the review to be entitled
37 to a hearing under Article 3A of Chapter 150B of the General Statutes, the applicant must make
38 a written demand upon the State Fire Marshal for a hearing no later than 30 days after service
39 upon the applicant of the notification of the outcome.
40 (e) A licensee or permittee whose license or permit is suspended, revoked, or not renewed
41 shall surrender the license or permit to the State Fire Marshal within 30 days of the suspension,
42 revocation, or nonrenewal.
43 (f) During the suspension or revocation of any license or permit, the licensee or permittee
44 whose license or permit has been suspended or revoked shall not engage in or attempt or profess
45 to engage in any transaction or business for which a license or permit is required under this
46 Article or directly or indirectly own, control, or be employed in any manner by any firm, business,
47 or corporation for which a license or permit under this Article is required.
48 (g) If, during the period between the beginning of proceedings and the entry of an order
49 of suspension or revocation by the State Fire Marshal, a new license or permit has been issued to
50 the individual or firm charged, the order of suspension or revocation shall operate to suspend or
51 revoke, as the case may be, the new license or permit held by the individual or firm.
