1 (17) Failing to comply with an administrative or court order imposing a child
2 support obligation, after entry of a final judgment or order finding the
3 violation to have been willful.
4 (18) Failing to pay State income tax or comply with any administrative or court
5 order directing payment of State income tax, after entry of a final judgment or
6 order finding the violation to have been willful.
7 (19) Subject to G.S. 93B-8.1, conviction of a crime involving dishonesty or breach
8 of trust.
9 (20) Violating any other provision of this Article or any rule or regulation adopted
10 and promulgated pursuant to this Article.
11 (21) Any cause sufficient to deny, suspend, or revoke the license or permit under
12 any other provision of this Article.
13 "§ 58-82C-12. Cease and desist orders; period of revocation.
14 (a) Whenever the State Fire Marshal shall have reason to believe that any individual or
15 firm is or has been violating any provisions of this Article, the State Fire Marshal may issue and
16 deliver to the individual or firm an order to cease and desist the violation.
17 (b) Any order issued by the State Fire Marshal under this section shall contain or be
18 accompanied by a notice of opportunity for hearing which may provide that a hearing will be
19 held if and only if an individual or firm subject to the order requests a hearing within 30 days of
20 receipt of the order and notice. The order and notice shall be served by hand delivery by the State
21 Fire Marshal or by registered or certified mail.
22 (c) Failure to comply with a cease and desist order is cause for revocation of any or all
23 permits and licenses issued by the State Fire Marshal for a period of not less than six months and
24 not to exceed five years. If a new permit or license has been issued to the individual or firm, the
25 order of revocation shall operate effectively with respect to the new permits and licenses held by
26 the individual or firm.
27 (d) In the case of an applicant for a license or permit, violation of any provision of this
28 Article may constitute grounds for refusal of the application.
29 "§ 58-82C-13. Civil penalty; injunction.
30 (a) Any individual or firm who violates any provision of this Article or any rule or order
31 issued by the State Fire Marshal under this Article shall be subject to a civil penalty imposed by
32 the State Fire Marshal of not more than one thousand dollars ($1,000) for a first offense, not less
33 than one thousand dollars ($1,000) and not more than two thousand dollars ($2,000) for a second
34 offense, and not less than two thousand dollars ($2,000) or more than five thousand dollars
35 ($5,000) for a third or subsequent offense.
36 (b) Prior to subjecting any individual or firm to a civil penalty under this section, the State
37 Fire Marshal shall give written notice to the individual or firm by hand delivery or by registered
38 or certified mail of the existence of the violations. After a reasonable period of time after notice
39 is given, an order may be issued based on this section. The order must be delivered in accordance
40 with the provisions of G.S. 58-82C-12(b) and must notify the individual or firm of the right to a
41 hearing with respect to the order.
42 (c) In addition to other powers granted to the State Fire Marshal under this Article, the
43 State Fire Marshal may bring a civil action to enjoin a violation of any provision of this Article
44 or of any rule or order issued by the State Fire Marshal under this Article.
45 "§ 58-82C-14. Criminal penalty.
46 (a) Any individual or firm that willfully or intentionally violates any provision of this
47 Article or any order or rule of the State Fire Marshal shall be guilty of a Class 1 misdemeanor.
48 (b) It shall also constitute a Class 1 misdemeanor to willfully or intentionally do any of
49 the following:
50 (1) Obliterate the serial number on a fire suppression system or portable fire
51 extinguisher for the purposes of falsifying service records.
Senate Bill 874-First Edition Page 7

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (2) Improperly install a fire suppression system or improperly recharge, repair,
2 service, or test any fire suppression system or portable fire extinguisher.
3 (3) While holding a permit or license, allow another individual to use the permit
4 or license or permit number or license number or to use a license or permit or
5 license number or permit number other than his or her own valid license or
6 permit or license number or permit number.
7 (4) Use or permit the use of any license by an individual or firm other than the
8 one to whom the license is issued.
9 (5) Use any credential, method, means, or practice to impersonate a representative
10 of the State Fire Marshal or any local fire chief, fire marshal, or other fire
11 authority having jurisdiction.
12 (6) Engage in the business of installing, inspecting, recharging, repairing,
13 servicing, or testing portable fire extinguishers or fire suppression systems
14 except in conformity with the provisions of this Article and the applicable
15 rules and regulations of the State Fire Marshal.
16 (7) Fail to comply with a cease and desist order under G.S. 58-82C-12.
17 "§ 58-82C-15. Power of the State and local governments to regulate not limited.
18 (a) Nothing in this Article limits the power of the State or a unit of local government to
19 require the submission and approval of plans and specifications or to regulate the quality and
20 character of work performed by contractors for the protection of the public health and safety.
21 (b) No unit of local government shall impose any other requirements on individuals
22 licensed or permitted by the State Fire Marshal as set forth in this Article to prove competency
23 to conduct any activity covered by the license or permit."
24 SECTION 2. The Office of the State Fire Marshal may adopt temporary rules to
25 implement the provisions of this act. Any temporary rules adopted in accordance with this section
26 shall remain in effect until permanent rules that replace the temporary rules become effective.
27 SECTION 3. This act becomes effective October 1, 2026.
